        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="487" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d487">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Marshall Mission Files, Lot 54–D270:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">General <persName type="from">Marshall</persName> to President
                            <persName type="to">Truman</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-02-23">23 February
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>234. Knew nothing of Generalissimo’s request of 17 February 1946 (Your 407
                        refers<note n="47" xml:id="d487fn47">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                    </note>). I did know however Government was keenly disappointed, at one point in
                    the negotiations, that ships were not turned over outright. Wedemeyer so
                    informed the Government upon receipt of 92330.<note n="48" xml:id="d487fn48">Telegram of January 10, not printed.</note> Reference your reply to the
                    Generalissimo, I recommend this matter be taken up on urgent basis by War
                    Department with the Chinese through Wedemeyer, after passage of legislation.
                    Colonel Davis, my representative in State Department, is familiar with all
                    details and can lend valuable assistance to procedure.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
